Beatrice Wynn, Stillwater’s historian and archivist, lived in a gingerbread-trimmed cottage that seemed to be slowly digesting its own collection of books, papers, and artifacts. The air inside was a potpourri of crumbling paper, beeswax polish, and damp wool. She was a woman in her late seventies, with eyes the color of flint behind thick lenses, and a manner that suggested she tolerated the present as a poorly written sequel to a much better past.

She listened to Crowe’s carefully edited questions—about the tower’s mechanics, about town rituals—while pouring tea into delicate, chipped cups.

“The Solstice Bonfire,” she said, settling into a wingback chair that sighed a cloud of dust. “You’ve seen it. The town’s great purge. We burn the old year’s regrets. A charming tradition, if you ignore the genesis.”

“Which was?” Crowe asked, the image of the empty compartment hovering in his mind.

“Fire,” Beatrice said flatly. “December 21st, 1947. The old Grange Hall, where the War Memorial stands now. It burned to the ground during the children’s Christmas pageant rehearsal. Three children died. The Caffrey twins, age eight, and little Maisie Vance, age six.”

The name Vance landed like a stone in the room’s quiet.

“A furnace fault, they said. Later, they blamed a vagrant—a man named Jonah Hatch, passing through. He was run out of town, nearly lynched. The story served. It gave the grief a shape, a villain to focus on. But the fire… it started in a locked storage closet where the children were fetching costumes. A place a stranger wouldn’t know, couldn’t access.”

Crowe felt the pieces begin to drift, like iron filings near a magnet. “And the bonfire?”

“Started the next year. A ‘cleansing flame.’ A way to ritually burn the tragedy, to keep the dark at bay on the longest night. We’re very good at ritual here, Detective. It papers over the cracks.”

“And the vagrant? Hatch?”

Beatrice’s lips thinned. “A convenient ghost. The families with power—the Vances, the McCulloughs, the Frosts—they closed ranks. An accident was bad for the town. A murder by a stranger was a tragedy. But a murder by one of their own?” She let the sentence hang, its implication fouling the scented air. “That would have been an apocalypse.”

“You think it was one of them.”

“I think the gearwork of this town is more complex than the one in that tower,” she said, gesturing vaguely upward. “Things mesh. Power is transferred. Sometimes, a piece is sacrificed to keep the whole mechanism from shattering.”

“Maisie Vance,” Crowe pressed. “Eleanor’s… aunt?”

“Great-aunt. Eleanor’s grandfather, Alistair Vance, was Maisie’s older brother. He was ten when she died. He never spoke of it, they say. Built the library instead. A temple to quiet, to order. The opposite of fire and chaos.” She sipped her tea. “Thorne’s project must have felt like a desecration. Not just of a building, but of a shrine.”

Crowe leaned forward. “The clock tower land. Who owned it in 1947?”

Beatrice didn’t even blink. “The Vances. That whole hill was Vance land. The tower was built by Alistair’s grandfather. A vanity project that became a town landmark.” She set her cup down with a precise click. “When Alistair built the library adjacent to it, he donated the tower to the town in perpetuity. A sentimental gesture, with a lawyer’s teeth in it. The deed has covenants. It can only be used as a clock tower or a public monument. Or so we thought.”

“Thorne found a way around the covenants.”

